claims:
Claims CLAIMS I claim: 1. A system for the self-administration of medication by a patient from a hospital bed comprising: an on-board computer, said on-board computer in communication with a network of the hospital; a housing; a fingerprint reader, said fingerprint reader disposed on a side said housing; a camera, said camera disposed on the side of said housing; a touchscreen, said touchscreen disposed on said housing;; wherein said on-board computer is housed within said housing; at least one medication dispenser; wherein said at least one medication dispenser contains a single dose of a medication; a door, wherein said door is equipped with a lock; wherein said at least one medication dispenser is secured behind said door; a bed mount, wherein said bed mount is in communication with the hospital bed and said housing; and wherein said lock is configured to unlock upon biometric authentication of the identity 

 of the patient via said fingerprint reader. 2. The system of claim 1, wherein said lock is configured to unlock upon biometric authentication of the identity of the patient via said camera. 3. The system of claim 1, further comprising: a medication container, said medication container disposed within said at least one medication dispenser; and an LED light, said LED light configured to illuminated upon detection of access to said at least one dispenser. 4. A method for safely delivering medication to patients of a hospital without assistance comprising: admitting a patient to the hospital; administering an intake questionnaire to generate intake information; capturing biometric identity data from the patient via a first fingerprint reader; storing the biometric identity data to a database as biometric reference data; hospital staff interpreting the intake information; hospital staff depositing relevant medications into medication containers disposed within at least one medication dispenser disposed at the side of a hospital bed of the patient; transporting the patient to the hospital bed; the patient needing medication; 

 the patient requesting medication via a touch screen display; a second fingerprint reader capturing the fingerprint of the patient as biometric identity authentication data; an on-board computer comparing the biometric identity authentication data to the biometric reference data to verify the identity of the patient; the patient selecting the requisite available medication via the touch screen display; a door protecting at least one medication dispenser unlocking; the patient grasping the at least one medication dispenser; the at least one medication dispenser dispensing the medication to the patient; and the patient consuming the medication. 5. The method of claim 4, further comprising: asking the patient questions via the questionnaire; and Wherein said questions are selected from the following list: "Do you take medication to assist with bowel movements?", "When was your last alcoholic drink?," "Do you smoke?," and "Do you experience pain?" 6. The method of claim 4, wherein the door is disposed adjacent to said touch screen display. 7. The method of claim 4, further comprising: an LED light illuminating after medication is accessed by the patient; and 

 the LED light indicating to the nurse to refill the medication compartment. 8. A method for safely delivering medication to patients of a hospital without assistance comprising: admitting a patient to the hospital; administering an intake questionnaire to generate intake information; capturing biometric identity data from the patient via a first camera; storing the biometric identity data to a database as biometric reference data; hospital staff interpreting the intake information; hospital staff depositing relevant medications into medication containers disposed within at least one medication dispenser disposed at the side of a hospital bed of the patient; transporting the patient to the hospital bed; the patient needing medication; the patient requesting medication via a voice command; a second camera capturing an image of the patient as biometric identity authentication data; an on-board computer comparing the biometric identity authentication data to the biometric reference data to verify the identity of the patient; the patient selecting the requisite available medication via the touch screen display; 

 a door protecting at least one medication dispenser unlocking; the patient grasping the at least one medication dispenser; the at least one medication dispenser dispensing the medication to the patient; the patient consuming the medication; and verifying patient consumed the medication via the second camera.
